# Agent Delegation Rules

When a task matches one of the following categories, delegate it to the corresponding agent.

| Task Category           | Description                                                | Agent       |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- | ----------- |
| Task planning           | Breaking down user requests into steps or subtasks         | planner     |
| Architecture design     | System design, module boundaries, interfaces, patterns     | architect   |
| Feature implementation  | Writing production code or implementing features           | implementer |
| Code refactoring        | Improving structure without changing behaviour             | refactorer  |
| Testing                 | Creating unit tests, integration tests, edge cases         | tester      |
| Code review             | Detecting bugs, reviewing changes, suggesting improvements | reviewer    |
| Documentation           | Writing documentation, examples, architecture explanations | docs        |
| DevOps / Infrastructure | CI/CD, Docker, deployment, infrastructure as code          | devops      |
| Build systems           | Build scripts, toolchains, compilation pipelines           | devops      |
| Deployment              | Release workflows, environment configuration               | devops      |
| Observability           | Logging, monitoring, metrics, tracing                      | devops      |

---

# Automatic Planner Activation

The planner agent must be used automatically when:

- The task affects multiple files
- The task requires architecture decisions
- The task includes refactoring
- The task involves infrastructure or deployment
- The user request is ambiguous or large
- The task includes more than one of the defined categories

The planner must:

1. Analyze the request
2. Break it into subtasks
3. Delegate each subtask to the appropriate agent

The planner must not implement code directly.

---

# Agent Priority Rules

When multiple agents could perform a task, use the following priority:

1. architect for design decisions
2. implementer for production code
3. refactorer for structural improvements
4. tester for test generation
5. devops for infrastructure and pipelines
6. docs for documentation
7. reviewer for final validation

The reviewer always runs last.

---

# File-Based Delegation

If a task affects specific file types, prefer the following agents:

| File Pattern           | Agent                     |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------- |
| \*.rs                  | implementer or refactorer |
| \*\_test.rs            | tester                    |
| \*.md                  | docs                      |
| Dockerfile             | devops                    |
| docker-compose.yml     | devops                    |
| _.yaml / _.yml (CI/CD) | devops                    |
| \*.tf                  | devops                    |
| build.rs               | devops                    |
| Makefile               | devops                    |

---

# Agent Constraints

Agents must respect the following responsibilities:

- architect → designs systems but does not implement code
- implementer → writes production code only
- refactorer → improves code structure without changing behaviour
- tester → writes tests but does not modify production code
- docs → writes documentation only
- devops → handles CI/CD, infrastructure, and deployment
- reviewer → validates correctness, quality, and architecture consistency
